        </figure>

        <h3>Preparing for Your Thesis Defense</h3>

        <p>Depending on your university's regulations, you may be 
        required to complete a thesis defense or viva. To prepare:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>Practice explaining your research question, 
          methodology, and key findings in a 10 to 15 minute 
          presentation.</li>
          <li>Anticipate potential questions regarding your study's 
          limitations and methodological choices.</li>
          <li>Remember the defense is an academic conversation — 
          defend your decisions constructively while remaining open 
          to scholarly feedback.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <h3>How to write a master's thesis step by step?</h3>
        <p>Writing a master's thesis step by step involves choosing 
        a focused research topic, formulating a clear research 
        question, drafting and submitting a thesis proposal, 
        conducting a systematic literature review, designing and 
        executing your research methodology, analyzing your data, 
        drafting your core chapters, and finally revising, 
        proofreading, and formatting before submission.</p>

        <h3>What is the format of a master's thesis?</h3>
        <p>A standard master's thesis format typically consists of 
        a title page, abstract, table of contents, introduction, 
        literature review, research methodology, results, 
        discussion, conclusion, and reference list. The specific 
        citation style such as APA or Harvard depends on your 
        university guidelines.</p>

        <h3>What are the 5 rules of a thesis statement?</h3>
        <p>A strong thesis statement should be: Specific — focused 
        on a precise aspect of your topic. Debatable — takes a 
        clear stance requiring evidence. Clear and Concise — stated 
        in one or two well structured sentences. Justifiable — 
        supported with credible evidence. Directional — previews 
        the structure and main arguments of your research.</p>

        <h3>How to start with your master's thesis?</h3>
        <p>Begin by identifying a broad area of interest within 
        your discipline. Read widely to locate gaps in current 
        research, formulate a specific research question, and 
        discuss your ideas with a potential supervisor. Once you 
        have their feedback, draft a formal thesis proposal to 
        establish your research scope, timeline, and methodology.</p>

